            </p>
            <article class="post-summary">
                  Programmers love to argue about coding standards, and one of the most contentious points is whether or not it should be allowed to use the equivalen to the &ldquo;auto&rdquo; keyword in C++ (in C# it&rsquo;s called &ldquo;var&rdquo;, other language shave similar things). This is a keyword that does simple type propagation and lets you name a value without explicitly giving its type.
I don&rsquo;t actually care all that much about coding standards, but this one bugs me because it seems to me that the main argument against allowing &ldquo;auto&rdquo; is a very transparent post-hoc justifications for &ldquo;It&rsquo;s unfamiliar to me, therefore bad&rdquo;.
